    <div class="sec-t">About</div>
    <p>Tromsø is located at 69.6°N, directly beneath the auroral oval — a ring-shaped region centred on the Earth's magnetic pole where charged solar particles most frequently collide with atmospheric gases to produce the aurora borealis. This positioning means Tromsø has statistically higher aurora frequency than most other populated locations on Earth. <strong>The Northern Lights season in Tromsø runs from September to March</strong>, when nights are dark enough for the display to be visible. During the midnight sun period (May to July), the sky never darkens sufficiently for aurora observation regardless of solar activity.</p>
    <p>The aurora is produced when charged particles from the sun, carried on the solar wind, interact with oxygen and nitrogen molecules in the upper atmosphere at altitudes of 100–300 kilometres. <strong>Green aurora (the most common) is produced by oxygen at around 100 km altitude</strong>; red aurora occurs at higher altitudes; blue and purple tones result from nitrogen interactions. Activity is measured by the KP index, a scale from 0 to 9. From Tromsø, aurora is typically visible at KP 3 or above. The equinoxes — late September and late March — historically show higher solar activity due to the Russell-McPherron effect, making them statistically the most active aurora periods.</p>
    <p>The aurora is visible from within Tromsø city on clear nights with sufficient activity, though <strong>light pollution from the city centre reduces visibility of fainter displays</strong>. Moving to darker locations on the outskirts of the island or driving 20–30 km out of the city improves the viewing experience significantly. The Norwegian Meteorological Institute (yr.no) provides cloud cover forecasts; the Norwegian Centre for Space Weather (spaceweather.no) provides KP forecasts. Organised aurora chase tours available from Tromsø operators typically cost 1,000–2,500 NOK per person and provide transport to low-light-pollution locations with a guide.</p>
