    <div class="sec-t">FAQ</div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">When is the best time to see the Northern Lights in Tromsø?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">The season runs September to March. Peak solar activity statistically occurs around the autumn and spring equinoxes — late September and late March. The darkest months (November to January) offer the longest viewing windows each night. March combines high activity probability with improving temperatures.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">Is it free to see the Northern Lights in Tromsø?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">Yes. The aurora borealis is a free natural phenomenon visible from any outdoor location with a dark, clear sky. Any website selling a "Northern Lights ticket" or "aurora experience" is selling a tour, transport service, or guided trip — not access to the lights themselves.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">Where is the best place to see the Northern Lights in Tromsø?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">The key requirement is darkness and a clear sky. Moving away from the city centre reduces light pollution. The shores of Tromsøya outside the centre, the Tromsdalen valley across the bridge, and elevated viewpoints like Fjellheisen summit all work well. Organised tours drive 20–30 km from the city to rural dark-sky locations.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">How do I know if Northern Lights will be visible tonight?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">Check yr.no for cloud cover in the Tromsø area — clear sky is essential. Check spaceweather.no for the KP index forecast. A KP of 3 or higher combined with a clear sky typically produces visible aurora from Tromsø. KP 5 or above is visible from the city centre despite moderate light pollution.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">Do I need a tour to see the Northern Lights?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">No. The aurora is visible from within Tromsø city on clear nights with sufficient solar activity. Organised tours (typically 1,000–2,500 NOK) provide transport to darker locations and a guide, but are not required. Renting a car and driving 20–30 km from the city is a lower-cost self-guided alternative.</div>
    </div>
